The '''2026 FIFA World Cup final''' will be the final match of the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026 World Cup]], the 23rd edition of [[FIFA]]'s competition for [[List of men's national association football teams|men's national soccer teams]]. The match is scheduled to be played at [[MetLife Stadium]] at the [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], near [[New York City]], on July 19, 2026.

==Background==
FIFA announced the date of the final on March 16, 2023.<ref>{{cite press release |date=March 16, 2023 |title=Date set for FIFA World Cup 26 final |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/articles/date-set-for-2026-world-cup-final-canada-mexico-usa |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref> The host of the final, MetLife Stadium, was announced by FIFA on February 4, 2024.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dominski |first=Michael |date=February 4, 2024 |title=World Cup 2026 schedule announcement live updates: Latest as FIFA selects host city for final |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/world-cup-2026-schedule-announcement-live-updates-final/r7oDr4oG9qK4/ |work=[[The Athletic]] |url-access=subscription |access-date=February 4, 2024}}</ref> The announcement was originally anticipated for late 2023, but was delayed amid planning difficulties.<ref>{{cite news |last=Panja |first=Tariq |date=September 15, 2023 |title=FIFA Delays Have Cities Worried About 2026 World Cup Plans |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/09/15/sports/soccer/2026-world-cup.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |url-access=limited |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref>

==Venue==
The selected host venue for the final is [[MetLife Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], {{convert|10|mi|km}} west of [[New York City]].<ref name="AP-Stadium"/> During the tournament, FIFA will refer to the venue as "New York New Jersey Stadium" due to its sponsorship policies and branded signage will be covered or removed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bowman |first=Emma |date=February 4, 2024 |title=The 2026 World Cup final will take place at New Jersey's MetLife Stadium |url=https://www.npr.org/2024/02/04/1229073496/2026-world-cup-final-nyc-nj-metlife-stadium |publisher=[[NPR]] |accessdate=February 7, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mather |first=Victor |date=April 17, 2026 |title=New York New Jersey Stadium? Why MetLife Is Changing Its Name for the World Cup |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/17/nyregion/fifa-world-cup-stadium-names-sponsors.html |work=The New York Times |url-access=limited |accessdate=April 26, 2026}}</ref> MetLife Stadium has primarily been used by the [[New York Giants]] and [[New York Jets]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL) since it opened in 2009.<ref name="AP-Stadium">{{cite news |last=Blum |first=Ronald |date=February 4, 2024 |title=2026 World Cup final will be played at MetLife Stadium in New Jersey |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/soccer/2024/02/04/2026-world-cup-schedule/1c65f7a0-c3a0-11ee-bbc9-9b5ca9b20779_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=February 4, 2024}}</ref> It has a listed capacity of 82,500 seats and previously hosted [[Super Bowl XLVIII]] in 2014,<ref name="NYTimes-NYNJ">{{cite news |last=Waldstein |first=David |date=February 9, 2024 |title='New York New Jersey' Got the World Cup Final. Now Comes the Hard Part. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2024/02/09/nyregion/new-york-new-jersey-world-cup-final.html |work=The New York Times |url-access=limited |accessdate=February 13, 2024}}</ref> the [[Copa América Centenario final]] in 2016,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Anzidei |first1=Melaine |last2=Rampling |first2=Ali |date=February 4, 2024 |title=New Jersey's MetLife Stadium wins the 2026 World Cup final |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5241468/2024/02/04/world-cup-final-2026-new-jersey/ |work=The Athletic |url-access=subscription |access-date=February 4, 2024}}</ref> and [[2025 FIFA Club World Cup final]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Deen |first=Safid |date=September 28, 2024 |title=2025 FIFA Club World Cup final set: Where games will be played in U.S. |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2024/09/28/fifa-club-world-cup-2025-game-sites/75434506007/ |work=USA Today |accessdate=October 14, 2024}}</ref>

The stadium is also scheduled to host seven other matches apart from the final match during the World Cup. During the tournament, the [[Meadowlands Rail Line]], a shuttle train with no regular service,<ref>{{cite news |last=Nessen |first=Stephen |date=February 6, 2024 |title=Is NJ Transit up for hosting the World Cup in 2026? Commuters are skeptical. |url=https://gothamist.com/news/nj-transit-world-cup-train-delays-2014-super-bowl |work=[[Gothamist]] |accessdate=February 13, 2024}}</ref> and a new $35&nbsp;million [[Bus lane|busway]] are planned to be used to transport attendees from the nearest transit hub at [[Secaucus Junction]].<ref name="AP-Stadium"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Higgs |first=Larry |date=February 6, 2024 |title=NJ Transit will operate 'on steroids' during the World Cup, Murphy says. Here's the plan. |url=https://www.nj.com/news/2024/02/nj-transit-will-operate-on-steroids-during-the-world-cup-murphy-says-heres-the-plan.html |work=[[NJ.com]] |url-access=subscription |accessdate=February 13, 2024}}</ref> [[NJ Transit]], the operator of both services, plans to issue $150 tickets for the train service with dedicated queues at [[New York Penn Station]] and $80 fares for buses. These costs, which are higher than normal event prices for MetLife Stadium services, were announced to offset the $48{{nbsp}}million cost of providing event service and security that was not subsidized by FIFA and other grants.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chen |first=Stefanos |date=April 17, 2026 |title=World Cup Transit Prices Are Set: $150 by Train and $80 for Shuttles |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/17/nyregion/nj-transit-world-cup-ticket-prices.html |work=The New York Times |url-access=limited |accessdate=April 26, 2026}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=April 17, 2026 |title=World Cup fans to MetLife Stadium will pay $150 train fares - NJ Transit |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/48514008/world-cup-fans-metlife-stadium-pay150-dollar-train-fares-nj-transit |publisher=ESPN |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=April 26, 2026}}</ref> In May 2026, NJ Transit announced that sponsorships and other funds raised would allow the fares to be cut by 30%, from $150 to $105.<ref>Enuco, Matthew. [https://www.nj.com/news/2026/05/nj-transit-reduces-controversial-world-cup-ticket-prices.html "NJ Transit reduces controversial World Cup ticket prices"], ''[[NJ.com]]'', May 7, 2026. Accessed May 7, 2026. "NJ Transit plans to reduce round-trip train ticket prices for the World Cup by 30% after initially setting them at $150. Daily ticket prices to ride by train to the international soccer tournament will be cut by $45 to $105 after support from “sponsorships and other sources” helped offset the higher prices, according to a statement from NJ Transit."</ref>

===Host selection===

The [[United 2026 FIFA World Cup bid|United 2026]] bid—composed of the United States, Mexico, and Canada—was chosen to host the 2026 World Cup by [[FIFA]] during the [[68th FIFA Congress]] on June 13, 2018. The bid planned to use 16 host cities spread across the three countries, with all matches from the quarterfinals onward played in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Panja |first1=Tariq |last2=Das |first2=Andrew |date=June 13, 2018 |title=World Cup 2026: United States, Canada and Mexico Win Bid to Be Host |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/13/sports/world-cup/fifa-2026-vote-north-america-morocco.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Belam |first=Martin |date=June 13, 2018 |title=Three hosts, 48 teams: how the 2026 World Cup will work |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jun/13/three-hosts-48-teams-how-the-2026-world-cup-will-work-united |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref> The venue for the final was not confirmed at the time, with MetLife Stadium named an early frontrunner due to its proximity to New York City and prior experience as host for major sporting events.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |author-link=Steven Goff |date=June 16, 2018 |title=2026 World Cup host cities: Ranking the contenders |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2018/06/16/2026-world-cup-host-cities-ranking-the-contenders/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Conway |first=Richard |date=June 13, 2018 |title=World Cup 2026: How US, Canada & Mexico won right to host tournament |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44465069 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sherman |first=Ted |date=September 23, 2021 |title=Will MetLife Stadium be home to the 2026 World Cup finals? N.Y. and N.J. hope to score a slot with FIFA. |url=https://www.nj.com/news/2021/09/will-metlife-stadium-be-home-to-the-2026-world-cup-finals-ny-and-nj-hope-to-score-a-slot-with-fifa.html |work=[[NJ.com]] |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref> Its main competitor was [[SoFi Stadium]], a new stadium in [[Inglewood, California]], near [[Los Angeles]], which was among the ten U.S. stadiums announced in June 2022. The [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]] in [[Pasadena, California]], the Los Angeles area venue that hosted the [[1994 FIFA World Cup final|1994 men's final]] and [[1999 FIFA Women's World Cup final|1999 women's final]], was not chosen for the tournament due to its age.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 16, 2022 |title=World Cup 2026 host cities confirmed: What you need to know about the 16 venues |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/37628821/need-know-16-venues |publisher=[[FIFA]] |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref>

SoFi Stadium was designed primarily for [[American football]] with a field that is {{convert|69|yd|m}} wide—narrower than FIFA's recommended dimensions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=August 3, 2022 |title=Leagues Cup friendlies showing L.A. is a soccer market |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/story/2022-08-03/galaxy-chivas-de-guadalajara-lafc-club-america-recap-leagues-cup |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref> According to media reports, the stadium's owner, [[Kroenke Sports & Entertainment]], was also unhappy with the revenue-sharing deal proposed by FIFA and threatened to cancel their plans to host World Cup matches.<ref>{{cite news |last=Crafton |first=Adam |date=September 21, 2023 |title=Kroenkes in dispute with FIFA over SoFi Stadium deal for 2026 World Cup |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4882751/2023/09/21/world-cup-2026-kroenkes-sofi-fifa/ |work=[[The Athletic]] |url-access=subscription |access-date=January 18, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bushnell |first=Henry |date=November 2, 2023 |title=LA-FIFA standoff at center of 2026 World Cup's first battle: Who's paying for it? |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/2026-world-cup-fifa-los-angeles-standoff-185240509.html |work=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref> In early 2023, [[AT&T Stadium]] in the [[Dallas]] area emerged as a potential host for the final due to its higher capacity of 90,000 seats and scheduled renovations to accommodate a wider field.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nudelstejer |first=Abraham |date=March 15, 2023 |title=FIFA delegation visits AT&T Stadium to offer insight on World Cup-prompted renovations |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/fc-dallas/2023/03/15/fifa-delegation-visits-att-stadium-to-offer-insight-on-world-cup-prompted-renovations/ |work=[[Dallas Morning News]] |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wilen |first=Holden |date=January 18, 2024 |title=Some think DFW has already secured 2026 World Cup final |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/news/2024/01/18/fifa-world-cup-final-possibly-in-dallas-arlington.html |work=[[Dallas Business Journal]] |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref> In January 2024, MetLife Stadium announced similar plans to widen its field for the World Cup by removing 1,740 seats in the corners.<ref>{{cite news |date=January 4, 2024 |title=MetLife Stadium to remove 1,740 seats in bid to host 2026 World Cup final |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/jan/04/metlife-stadium-world-cup-final-2026-seating |work=The Guardian |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=January 18, 2024}}</ref> According to ''[[The Athletic]]'', the selection of MetLife Stadium came as a "surprise" to local officials, who organized a small viewing party for the announcement. Dallas's bid had been favored—and rumored as the winner in January—and included a simulcast of the match at two nearby venues to increase ticket revenue.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Anzidei |first1=Melanie |last2=Crafton |first2=Adam |date=February 5, 2024 |title=Inside the World Cup 2026 final host city selection: Why New Jersey was picked over Dallas |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5252093/2024/02/05/world-cup-2026-final-metlife-stadium-selection-process/ |work=The Athletic |url-access=subscription |access-date=February 7, 2024}}</ref>

==Entertainment==
<!--{{main|2026 FIFA World Cup final halftime show}}-->
[[File:2026 FIFA World Cup Final Halftime Show.svg|thumb|Logo of the 2026 FIFA World Cup final halftime show]]
On September 28, 2024, FIFA announced that [[Global Citizen (organization)|Global Citizen]] would co-produce a [[halftime show]] for the World Cup final, similar to those in the NFL's [[Super Bowl]]. It will be the first halftime show in the history of the FIFA World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |date=September 28, 2024 |title=Global Citizen to Produce Halftime Show for FIFA World Cup Final, Starting in 2026 |url=https://variety.com/2024/music/news/world-cup-final-halftime-show-global-citizen-produce-fifa-starting-2026-1236158976/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=September 30, 2024}}</ref> On March 5, 2025, FIFA announced that [[Coldplay]] would assist with the final list of performers while also organizing a concert in [[Times Square]] during the weekend of the final.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ogden |first=Mark |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/44117914/2026-world-cup-final-host-super-bowl-style-half-show|title=Coldplay to plan '26 World Cup final halftime show|date=March 5, 2025|publisher=ESPN}}</ref> On May 13, 2026, it was announced that [[Madonna]], [[Shakira]], and [[BTS]] would headline the halftime show and the show will be between 11 and 15 minutes long.<ref name=":0">{{cite news |last=McKenna |first=Lorraine |date=May 14, 2026 |title=Madonna, Shakira & BTS to headline World Cup show |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c5yrl54561do |access-date=May 14, 2026 |website=[[BBC Sport]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260514111629/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c5yrl54561do |archive-date=May 14, 2026 |url-status=live}}</ref> The show also aims to raise 100 million dollars for the [[FIFA Global Citizen Education Fund]].<ref name=":0" />

